sbol:Collection.dcterms:title: iGEM Parts Registry
sbol:Collection.dcterms:description: The iGEM Registry is a growing collection of genetic parts that can be mixed and matched to build synthetic biology devices and systems. As part of the synthetic biology community's efforts to make biology easier to engineer, it provides a source of genetic parts to iGEM teams and academic labs.

sbol:ComponentDefinition.dcterms:title: BBa_K772103
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableDescription:
GFP - LacZ protein generator is generated with the aim of inducing a reporting reaction aftermath of the activation of EpCAM detection system. (BBa_K772100)
For more information: BBa_K772006
sbol:ComponentDefinition.dc:creator: Mustafa Elitok
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableProvenance: Cleavage site, LacZ and GFP sequences are gathered from Registry.
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableNotes: To achieve a constitutive production, pTetR promoter is added in the upstream region of the original part.

sbol:ComponentDefinition.dcterms:title: p(tetR)
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableDescription: Sequence for pTet inverting regulator driven by the TetR protein.
sbol:ComponentDefinition.dc:creator: June Rhee, Connie Tao, Ty Thomson, Louis Waldman
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableProvenance: Lutz, R., Bujard, H., Nucleic Acids Research (1997) 25, 1203-1210.
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableNotes: BBa_R0040 TetR-Regulated Promoter is based on a cI promoter. It has been modified to include two TetR binding sites and the BioBrick standard assembly head and tail restriction sites.

sbol:ComponentDefinition.dcterms:title: AnRe
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableDescription: This part contains a green fluorescent protein (GFP) as a non-reactive chemical compound (anchor) in order to neutralize the active reactive fixed to it, a reporter/inducer device or protein (enzyme etc.) and a TEV protease cleavage site between them to assemble these two proteins. BBa_772001 and BBa_K772002 are assembled to be used as the trigger of detection in the whole system which ends with the intracellular transfection (or activation) of TEV protease. After the activation, it is planned that TEV protease will cleave this anchor-inducer protein complex to release free the inducer/reporter. In conclusion, the inducer would activate a transcription pathway on the targeted inducible gene or the reporter would indicate that there is a change in the whole system.
sbol:ComponentDefinition.dc:creator: Mustafa Elitok
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableProvenance: Cleavage site, LacZ and GFP sequences are gathered from Registry.
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableNotes: Note that there is an RBS sequence just before the protein sequence in order to eliminate the need of addition of it.
